<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-30T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-30T05:00:00-05:00" n="138" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002 Manchuria/129: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>)
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-30T18:00:00+08:00">June 30, 1932—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 30—4:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>319. Supplementing my June 30, 5 p.m., the Inspector General ordered the
                            Commissioner to come to Shanghai in order that he might be saved
                            embarrassment but he refused presumably at the instance of the chief of
                            the section of Foreign Affairs.</p>
                        <p>Not repeated to the Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>